  "prompt": "What is dyarchy and when was it introduced in India?",
  "response": "Dyarchy is a system of double government that was introduced in British India by the Government of India Act of 1919, also known as the Montagu-Chelmsford Reforms. Under dyarchy, provincial governments were divided into two categories: \"transferred\" subjects, which were given to Indian ministers responsible to the legislative councils, and \"reserved\" subjects, which remained under the control of the British-appointed governor and his executive council.\n\nThe intent behind dyarchy was to provide a level of self-governance to Indians while retaining crucial areas of administration under British control. The introduction of dyarchy marked the first time that Indians were allowed to hold significant administrative positions in provincial governments, although the powers they received were limited.\n\nTo sum up, dyarchy was introduced in India in 1919 as part of the Government of India Act 1919 (Montagu-Chelmsford Reforms).",
